Well, lemme tell ya, I'm thinkin' about gettin' into this social work thing, maybe workin' with kids that been messed up or families that are fallin' apart. I reckon I got some good stuff to bring to the table, ya know? Like, I'm all about helpin' folks, treatin' everyone with respect, doin' the right thing, and tryin' to make things better for folks. Not just for other folks, but for myself too, gotta keep learnin' and growin'.

See, I've always wanted to help folks out, but wasn't sure what kinda path to take. Back in high school and college, I saw folks runnin' from their problems, some doin' things that ain't right to cope.  So I got myself a Psychology degree, thought that might help. But after grad school, I took a break, ya know?  Then one day, I was visitin' a friend, and she had this sixteen-year-old kid sittin' on her couch lookin' scared. Turns out, he was runnin' from his abusive folks.  Next day, found out he called the police on 'em. Figured I'd see if I could help, so I went to his parents' place.  Talked to the cops, told 'em I was a Psychology grad. They asked me to talk to the parents 'cause they couldn't do nothin'. When I talked to 'em, they seemed all nervous, makin' excuses about their son bein' a manipulator. That's when I realized, I need to be doin' somethin' for these kids, help 'em with their family messes.

And this social justice thing, that's important too. We say we care about individuals, but act like everyone's gotta be the same. I'm my own person, don't wanna be like everyone else.  In high school and college, I protested against what ain't right: dyed my hair crazy colors, wore what I wanted, pierced my ears, joined that Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance, stood up to racism and discrimination whenever I saw it. I believe in standin' up for what's right, and I'll keep doin' it.

Alright, so this here paper is gonna talk about two ways of lookin' at insomnia: the biological way and the social way. The biological folks, they're all about your genes and your body, see? Like, are you born with a knack for sleepin' or not? The social folks, they say it's all about your life, your friends, your job, where you come from - all that kinda stuff. This paper's gonna look at both sides, see what the research says, and then figure out what's good about each side and what ain't so good.

Now, sleep problems come in all shapes and sizes. Sometimes it's just you sleepin' wrong, like not gettin' enough or stayin' asleep. Other times it's tied to somethin' else goin' on in your head, like anxiety or depression. And sometimes it's 'cause you're sick or took somethin' that messes with your sleep.

There are different kinds of sleep problems, like insomnia (can't fall asleep), hypersomnia (can't stay awake), narcolepsy (fall asleep outta nowhere), sleep apnea (stop breathin' while you sleep), and more. And then there are the weird dreams and sleepwalkin' kinda things.

This paper's lookin' mostly at insomnia and how the biological and social things might cause it.

The biological side says it's all about your brain, see? There's this part of your brain called the hypothalamus that controls your sleepin' and wakin'. Turns out, there are special little parts in there called orexin neurons that tell you when to sleep and when to wake up.

This one study they did on mice found that these orexin neurons have somethin' called GABAB receptors, and when they get fired up, they make you sleepy. So if those receptors ain't workin' right, you might have trouble sleepin'. Like, maybe you were born with a messed up receptor, or maybe somethin' happened to it. Either way, you might need meds to help you sleep.

The social side of this says that if your family has a history of sleep problems, you might be more likely to have 'em too. And if you're stressed out or lonely or don't have a good job or whatever, that can mess with your sleep too.

So, it's like a mix of nature and nurture, right? Your genes and your environment both play a role in how well you sleep.

This here's a little somethin' somethin' about this here Central Auditory Processing Disorder, or CAPD for short. 

First off, we'll figure out what it is, like plain and simple. Then, we'll talk about how you tell if someone's got it, kinda like lookin' for red flags. Finally, we'll wrap it up with ways a teacher can help a kid with CAPD in a regular classroom. 

CAPD, well, it's when your brain, the big boss upstairs, ain't so good at makin' sense of what you hear. You can hear just fine, but your brain, it's like it's missin' a few gears. It can't separate words, can't tell what's important from all the background chatter. Kinda like tryin' to listen to a radio with too much static.

Now, folks have been talkin' about this kinda thing since the fifties, callin' it "auditory imperception." Back then, they were doin' tests on kids who had trouble talkin' and understandin'. They figured out these kids weren't deaf, but somethin' was goin' on in their brains.

CAPD can show up in all sorts of ways. Some folks can't tell where a sound is comin' from. Others can't tell the difference between two sounds, like a cat meow and a dog bark. Some folks can't put sounds together to make sense of things, like understandin' a joke.

To figure out if someone's got CAPD, you gotta watch 'em listen and do some tests. They might ask you questions, make you listen to different sounds, and see how you do. There ain't one surefire test, but they use somethin' to see if your brain's workin' right.

So this play, Twelfth Night, it's sayin' somethin' about how, like, when you put on a fake face for a long time, you gotta take it off, or you'll lose yourself, ya know?  It's like, you're wearin' a mask, and if you keep wearin' it, you forget who you are under there.  But, dang, sometimes folks get mad when you take the mask off. They feel tricked, and it messes up your friendships. So, you gotta think  – do ya keep the mask on to keep folks happy, or do ya take it off and risk makin' 'em mad?  It's a tough call.

Now, this whole pretendin' to be someone else thing gets real messy when it comes to gender. Like, why in the world would someone wanna pretend to be the opposite sex?  

In this play, Viola, she's gotta pretend to be a dude to stay safe. She's in a new place, and it's scary out there for a woman alone.  But, by doin' that, she cuts herself off from other women, ya know, the folks who usually understand what she's goin' through. And get this, she's so good at it that this lady, Olivia, falls for her!  Talk about a pickle.  

And then there's this other guy, Orsino, who's all lovesick for Viola, but she's pretendin' to be a guy, so it's all messed up. It's like, is Orsino really into Viola, or is he just into the idea of a guy bein' all sweet on him? It makes ya think, don't it?

This whole play, it's kinda like a mirror, showin' us how pretendin' can bring out all sorts of feelings we didn't even know we had.

Now listen up, y'all.  This here German thing, they weren't all bad, you know?  Sure, they went and did some real messed up stuff in South West Africa, like killin' a whole bunch of Ovaherero and Nama folks.  That ain't right, no sir. But they weren't all bad apples.  They had different ways of doin' things in their colonies, just like folks in Texas are different from folks in Maine.  Some places they built schools and taught folks how to read and write, like in East Africa, where the Brits took over later.  But in South West Africa, it was different.  They mostly left the teachin' up to the church folks, who didn't get much help from the government.  Now, they did spend a whole lotta money makin' sure the white folks in South West Africa got a good education, but the black folks, well, they didn't get the same deal.  That messed things up somethin' fierce, even after the Germans left.  This paper, it's tryin' to figure out why that happened in South West Africa and not in other places.  Seems like the folks who lived there and the folks in charge, they didn't treat the black folks the same way they treated the white folks.  There's a whole heap of books about this German colonial thing, but most of them are in German, written back when they were runnin' the place.  Some folks wrote about the different ways they ran things in each colony, and one fella, Cohen, he really looked at South West Africa and East Africa and figured out some of the reasons why they were so different.  He thinks it had somethin' to do with the fact that there were a whole lotta white folks livin' in South West Africa, which made things different than in places like East Africa.  South West Africa wasn't as hot as some other places, so more white folks moved there, and they wanted to make sure their kids got a good education.

Man, trying to figure out all the different kinds of popular music is like trying to herd cats! There's so many, it's crazy!  You got your rock, your country, your rap, your jazz, and a whole bunch more.  And get this, each one of those has a bunch of little branches, like sub-genres and stuff.  It's enough to make your head spin.

But let me tell ya, heavy metal, that's a wild ride! It's been around for about 40 years and it's exploded into a million different flavors.  It's like a big ol' pot of chili, with a whole bunch of spices thrown in.  Some of it's dark, some of it's crazy, some of it's just plain loud!  

And that's the thing about heavy metal, folks. It's not just music, it's a movement! It's about pushing the boundaries, about being loud and proud, about not being afraid to be different.  It's about more bass, more volume, more everything!   It's like these guys crank up the guitars and let loose, and it's pretty darn awesome.

But hey, where did it all come from?  Well, I gotta tell ya, some folks say it started back in the 70s when everyone was tripping out on drugs.  They were making music that sounded like it came from another planet, you know?  Dark, weird, and kinda scary.  

And it's still going strong today, with bands taking all those dark themes and running with them.  It's a wild ride, that's for sure.

Now listen up, this here artist guy, Rousseau, back in the day, he was dreamin' big, bigger than those fancy Surrealist fellas.  See, he was paintin' these dreamy pictures, like straight outta his head, ya know? One of his best, "The Dream," it's like a lady starin' in awe at somethin' wild and wonderful, like a dream come true.  But it ain't just about the lady, it's about Rousseau himself, his own dreams and hopes. He wanted folks to see his art, to say "Wow, that's somethin' special!" But here's the thing, he was stuck in a pickle. He wanted to be liked, to be a part of the fancy art crowd, but he also wanted to paint his own way, ya know, be unique, not just copy what everyone else was doin'. 

See, he wasn't born with a silver spoon, this Rousseau guy. He worked for the government, collectin' tolls, nothin' fancy.  He lost his wife and kids, so he turned to paintin' to make somethin' outta nothin'.  He wanted to be like those fancy painters, but he was startin' late, and they were already famous. It was tough bein' the new kid on the block. He wanted to be accepted, but he also wanted to be himself. He was caught between two worlds, ya know?  He just wanted folks to see his art and say, "Hey, this guy's got somethin' special!"

Lotsa brainiacs have said that bein' good and lookin' good, truth and beauty, go hand in hand. I reckon there's a reason for that. Like ol' Keats said, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." We learn most things through schoolin' or doin', but we just seem to *get* good and beautiful things, like Keats figured, without nobody teachin' us. Both bein' good and lookin' good, they're both about describin', not tellin' ya what to do. We study 'em to figure out why somethin's pretty or right, not to give rules on how to make 'em. 

Truth be told, ya can't ever fully explain what's good or what's pretty. Talkin' about da Vinci's Mona Lisa might bring up stuff like the front, the back, and the colors, but that don't really say why it's good art. When folks talk about their favorite art or book, they'll say somethin' like, "There's just somethin' about it," before they get all fancy-pants with words. I think art and bein' good can't be fully explained, ya know? Like Flannery O'Connor said, "A story is a way to say somethin' that can't be said any other way..." No matter how much we talk about a book, there's somethin' left over, somethin' special.  I think bein' good is the same way.

Morality and art hit us hard, deep down inside, somethin' we feel but can't quite put into words.  Books get us because they deal with values, like life itself.

Germany today is a real powerhouse, a united country with its own unique culture. You can feel it everywhere, from Munich in the Alps all the way to Kiel by the Baltic Sea. Same vibe in Cologne on the Rhine River, through the heart of Germany, to Dresden on the Elbe River. With a culture like that, it's no surprise that Germany today is made up of a bunch of different tribes and groups.

They call the land "Germania," but nobody really knows where that name came from. Some smart guys back in the day, like Tacitus, said it came from a German tribe called the Tungrians.  They were fighting the Gauls back then, way before they crossed the Rhine River.  Julius Caesar, he was the one who first used the word "Germanus" in his writings about fighting the Gauls. He used it to tell the difference between the Gauls he'd conquered and the Germans he hadn't. Some folks say it came from the Gauls themselves, or maybe it meant "neighbor" in their language. Caesar himself wrote about how the Germans were always fighting the Gauls, "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." 

Then there's Tacitus, a Roman historian who wrote in 98 AD about the origins of the Germans. He said they were pure, original people who hadn't mixed with other races. He thought they were so tough that no one would ever leave their warm homes in Asia or Africa to come live in chilly, wild Germany. 

The Romans, they weren't too interested in German land either. They would come in for resources and fight a few battles, but mostly they stayed in their own big empire. The Germans, though, they lived right on the edge of the Roman Empire, trading their stuff and even fighting for the Romans in their army.

Well, let me tell ya, I was lookin' at this mess in the bathroom and my mind just went blank.  I was lookin' at it, you know, like I was supposed to understand it, but it was just too much. My thoughts were flyin' around like mosquitos on a hot summer night, never landin' on nothin'. 

This one time, I got this book called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." This artist I knew told me to check it out. It's about learnin' how to draw, and it teaches ya all kinds of stuff about how your brain sees stuff.  One thing it says is to draw a square around what you're lookin' at, like makin' a picture outta just that one thing. It's supposed to make it easier to understand. 

But when I was lookin' at this mess in the bathroom, I couldn't do that. I was just too overwhelmed. I mean, Picasso had his blue period, Monet loved paintin' trees, and them Italian guys with their fancy colors.  I thought maybe this was gonna be my thing, my own masterpiece, my "Work in Brown".

So, I grabbed a mop, gotta look the part, right? But my hand just felt all shaky. It was like I was tryin' to do somethin' super important, but all I could think about was this dang brown thing stuck in the toilet.  I flushed and flushed, but it wouldn't budge.

I finally just grabbed the toilet paper and started wrapin' myself up like a mummy. Then I dipped my hand in the bowl, like I was gettin' the turkey outta the oven.

Look, teenagers are dyin' behind the wheel, and it ain't right. There's a whole bunch of reasons why this is happenin', but let me tell ya, it ain't just 'cause they're young and dumb. Those brainiacs at the National Institutes of Health say the teen brain ain't even ready for the dangers of drivin'. And let's face it, they ain't got much experience, which means more crashes, flip-overs, speedin', and drivin' off the road.

Now, we all know teenagers like to cruise around with their buddies, and that's a recipe for disaster. Some folks out in California did a study, and guess what? The more passengers, the more accidents.

So, some states are tryin' to fix this with these temporary licenses that limit how much teens can drive and who they can have in the car. But that ain't enough, in my opinion. The real problem is, young folks just ain't cut out for drivin' yet. This psychologist, Marvin Zuckerman, says even 18 is too young. He says kids under 20 just love takin' risks, and that's a dangerous game when you're behind the wheel.

So, what do we do? We gotta wait till they grow up a bit. Imagine all these Boomers' kids gettin' their licenses around 2010 - it's gonna be chaos!  

We need some good ol' fashioned laws to get this sorted.  Schools can still teach 'em about drivin', but nobody under 18 should be behind the wheel. They can get a learner's permit, practice with a grown-up, and then maybe, just maybe, they'll be ready.  We gotta do somethin', folks, before more kids end up hurtin' themselves or someone else.

Well, I was lookin' through some old Edison movies at the Library of Congress, y'know, the ones from way back in the day.  They had fifteen of these "trick" films, made between 1895 and 1901. These films, they're all about makin' things look like somethin' they ain't, usin' clever editing and whatnot. I spent a while watchin' 'em, tryin' to figure out how they made the tricks work. Most of 'em are pretty simple, stickin' to the same old stuff, but some of the later ones, they start gettin' a little more fancy.

See, back then, these trick films, they were all kinda filmed the same way.  Picture a stage, like in a theater. That's what these films looked like, all set up in front of the camera, no fancy movins' around.  The camera just sits there, like a statue, and the folks on stage, they just walk back and forth.  It's like they're stuck in a box. Take this one film, "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel," for instance.  The actors, they come in from one side, walk back and forth, and then outta the box, but the camera never follows 'em.

And 'cause of that stage setup, the shots, they're all pretty long, like you're way back in the audience.  Never any close-ups, none of that fancy stuff.  Just like in a play, you see the whole thing at once.


Now, most of these trick films, they're just one long shot, like one big chunk of film. That means they ain't very long, maybe just a minute or so. And they don't tell much of a story, just a bunch of quick tricks, like magic shows or disappearin' acts. But here's the thing: what looks like one shot to you, it might actually be a bunch of shots stitched together.  Take "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots," one of the oldest trick films. Looks like one shot, right? But look closer, and you'll see where they splice in the shot of the beheadin'.

John Taylor, this fella from Caroline, was a real firebrand when it came to this whole Republican thing.  He was mostly a farmer, but even that, along with his little stint in politics, made him a guy who spoke his mind about freedom and government. He believed, right down to his boots, that farming was the best way to live, and that shaped how he saw everything about the government.  He wanted to protect farming and make sure it thrived, and that's why he got all worked up about things like who’s in charge, what the Constitution says, and even how the courts work. 

Taylor thought America had a real chance to build something special because we weren’t tied down by old traditions.  He believed folks had natural rights, and he meant it – if one right gets taken away, they all get weaker.  He thought the government shouldn’t mess with those rights at all. He saw this “state of nature” thing as a mess where the strong and sneaky guys got ahead, but he thought civilization should be better than that.

To build this ideal society, Taylor thought the government had to be ready for the good and bad in people.  He was firm about this idea that people are both good and bad.  He said, “Since government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human.”  He thought good principles protect your stuff, help farming, and keep big business in check. He believed that a government based on good principles would work fair, no matter who's running it, because people are always gonna be greedy. He felt like people are driven by what they want, but it’s only bad when they try to get what they want by hurting others.  A good government keeps people from doing bad things, but it needs to be watched carefully so it doesn’t get bad itself.

Taylor, like a lot of other old-school Republicans, thought the Constitution should be followed exactly. He wanted a tiny federal government, with only the powers the Constitution said it had. He knew a big government would be expensive and could become a tyrant. But he thought just reading the words wasn't enough – you had to understand what the people who wrote it meant. He even thought the Declaration of Independence was more important because it talked about the states being separate and independent, not one big country.

Well, lemme tell ya, this here project, it started out strong, like a bull in a china shop! But then, come the third month, folks just stopped submittin' their commuter logs like it was nobody's business. Kinda made me scratch my head, ya know? See, it was winter up North, and folks ain't ridin' their bikes or walkin' much in the snow. Plus, December was a busy time for everyone, with school exams and holidays cheer. Fillin' out a log probably went right outta their minds. Then, poof! Holidays hit, and everyone took off for a month-long break. Didn't even need to be on campus. 

Then January rolled around, and still, not many logs. Figured maybe folks were just losin' steam, like a flat tire after a long drive.  So, we decided to shake things up with a "Carpool Challenge Week" in March, and wouldn't ya know it, more folks started loggin' their commutes.  

See, the trick with these kinda projects is keepin' folks interested. You gotta keep 'em motivated, ya know? Like a dog chasin' a squirrel, they need somethin' to chase after. Now, a lot of folks, they love their cars, independence and all that. It's like a way of life up here. So, we tried to give 'em somethin' to trade it for - gift certificates to restaurants, coffee shops, even a massage once in a while.  

Maybe we shoulda gone bigger, ya know? Like, a brand new bike, or even a fancy electric car.  That might've gotten folks riled up! Maybe we shoulda even upped the ante with those gift certificates as the project went on, like addin' in a couple of bikes in December, then a shiny new car in January.

Alright, let me break this down for ya, see?  An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is kinda like a big basket of investments, like a mutual fund, but you can buy and sell it like a regular stock on the market. You get all the benefits of owning a bunch of different things at once, like diversifying your risk, but you can even do fancy stuff like borrow money to buy more or even bet against it if you think it's gonna go down. Now, these things are usually cheaper to own than mutual funds, but you gotta pay a little fee every time you buy or sell, just like with regular stocks. 

The cool thing is, there's all kinds of ETFs out there, tracking different stuff, from the whole market to specific industries or even goofy things like gold or oil. So, you gotta do your homework and figure out if it's really giving you what it promises.

Let's take this ETF called IHF, for example. It's got a bunch of stocks inside, and I'm gonna look at the top ten, 'cause they make up most of the whole thing.  I'm gonna see if owning just those ten stocks is better than owning the whole ETF.

Now, I'm gonna figure out how much each of those stocks contributes to the ETF's overall performance, like how much risk it takes on and how much it makes.

Turns out, owning just those ten stocks might actually make you a bit more money and be a bit less risky than owning the whole ETF!  But, there's a chance that the difference might just be a fluke, ya know? So I gotta do some more checking to be sure.  I'm gonna look at how much each stock's price moves around compared to the whole ETF.  If it's different, then owning the ten stocks might be a better deal.

Poe, he was a smart fella, you know? He liked to brag about his poem "Dream-Land." In it, he uses this word "Thulé" twice, like a bookend thing. Now, some folks say he got that word from Virgil, this old writer who talked about an island way up north, like the edge of the world back then.  But here's the thing, Poe liked German writers a whole lot. 

This one guy, Arndt, he wrote a book comparing Poe to this German writer, Goethe.  He says Poe kinda copied Goethe's poem, "The King of Thulé."  See, Goethe's poem is about a king who loses his wife and gets real down in the dumps. He drinks too much, misses his wife like crazy, and ends up throwing himself off a cliff. Sounds kinda like Poe, don't it? 

Now, Goethe was a big deal, wrote this famous play called "Faust." And there's this part in it, "The King of Thulé," that Poe probably knew about. It's like a little story within a bigger story.

So, Poe used "Thulé" twice in his poems, like he was saying, "Hey, I'm thinking about this king and his sad story." It's like they're connected, you know? Poe's poem is all dark and lonely, just like Goethe's king. They both lost someone they loved and are feeling lost. 

Poe knew Goethe, even if it was just through other writers he admired. He was a smart guy, read a lot, and knew his stuff.

Alright, so this lady, Jennifer Palmer, took a nasty spill in a grocery store 'cause some dang applesauce was on the floor. Now, she wants some extra cash, what they call "punitive damages," 'cause she says the store manager, Paul Martin, acted real mean. See, somebody told him about the spill twice, but he just wanted to eat his dinner and didn't care. 

Now, the judge ain't gonna just toss this case out. To get those extra damages, Jennifer's gotta prove that Paul knew what he was doin' was gonna hurt somebody.  She's sayin' that Paul shoulda known better 'cause folks had been slipping and fallin' on spills all year long. Even with that, he didn't clean it up! Plus, she's sayin' Paul was just plain mean for not doin' his job.

Here's the whole story: On a Friday night, two of Paul's employees, Rich and Mary, told him about the applesauce on the floor. But Paul was busy eatin' and said he didn't have time for that sort of thing.  An hour later, Jennifer comes along and BAM! She slips and hurts her back real bad.  Turns out, there had been five other folks who slipped and fell that year!

Now, Jennifer's sayin' Paul knew this was a danger and didn't care. She's sayin' he's gotta pay for bein' careless and mean.

Alright, lemme tell ya somethin'. Back when I took this Islam class, like four years ago, we were always talkin' about whether Islam was a bad religion or not.  Seems like even more important now, ya know?  Lookin' back since 9/11, the media, they went from thinkin' Islam was the enemy to bein' all soft on it. You wouldn't have believed it back in 2001, havin' a prez candidate named Barack Obama, with that Muslim family history. 

Now, this biography of Muhammad, it's kinda weird, ya know? 'Cause what I thought I knew about Muhammad, he was all about conquerin' tribes and makin' 'em become Muslim. But this book, it paints him like some kinda martyr, misunderstood and humble. Like everyone just came to him 'cause they saw the truth, ya get me? 

And it's kinda funny, there's all these similarities between Jesus and Muhammad. Like, remember when Muhammad turned a small amount of mutton and milk into enough for forty guys?  It's like they're tryin' to make Muhammad look like some kinda miracle worker, like Jesus, but they're tryin' to steal his thunder, ya know?

They also got all these stories about how people converted to Islam on their own. But a lot of 'em are second-hand, like "So-and-so told me, who heard it from so-and-so." Kinda makes you wonder, don't it?

What really bugs me is they're tryin' to make Muhammad look like some super-good guy, humble and wise. But history says he wasn't so gentle, ya know? Makes me wonder if Muslims today know the real story about Muhammad.

Listen up, folks.  See, back when Jesus was preachin', things were different.  Now, over the years, Christianity's gone and changed a whole heap.  It's like takin' a good recipe and addin' in all sorts of stuff that ain't in the original.  These days, folks are gettin' more open-minded, seein' things in new ways.  But the old-timers, they stuck to their ways, you know, kinda like them rednecks who don't trust nothin' new.  But I reckon times are changin'.  

Folks are gonna start lookin' back, tryin' to figure out what Jesus really meant, what he truly preached.  It might take a while, maybe even a whole heap of time, but mark my words, folks are gonna go back to the basics.  It's gonna be like rewindin' the clock on Christianity, takin' away all the extra stuff that got added later.  Just like Jesus taught it, plain and simple.   

Now, when this happens, the churches, they'll still be there, leadin' the way.  But things ain't gonna be the same. All those different groups, all those different ways of doin' things, they're gonna start gettin' more alike.  It's like when the Romans, they used to persecute Christians, but then they became Christian themselves.  Or how things changed with African-Americans, goin' from slavery to bein' leaders.   This is gonna be just like that, only in the Christian world.  

But here's the kicker:  Folks are gonna start seein' Jesus' words in a different light, more like stories and lessons than hard and fast rules.   So, what happened after Jesus walked this earth?  Well, before him, there was Judaism, that's where it all began.  They believed in one God, readin' the scriptures as the truth, and that's what the early Christians believed too.  They weren't all the same, mind you, but that was the core of their faith.

Listen, I think that book, The Jungle, it really gets at somethin'.  People, deep down, they're kinda selfish, ya know? They just wanna take care of themselves and make things good for themselves. They don't give a hoot about anyone else, especially if they're below 'em.  

The book shows this with the big bosses, the guys runnin' the factories. All they care about is makin' their factories bigger and richer, no matter what. They don't care if folks get hurt or if the whole place is polluted.  Sinclair, the guy who wrote it, he tries to show how bad it is. He talks about how the factories are like black towers against the sky, spewin' smoke everywhere. He says the bosses don't care about the people or the animals gettin' sick from all that mess.

And the bosses, they don't care about the workers either. They'll do anything to save a buck. They make them work crazy hours and then just fire 'em without any warning.  Back then, there weren't no rules to protect the workers, so the bosses could do whatever they wanted. They made the workers go faster and faster, even if it meant workin' in terrible conditions.  The book doesn't say it straight out, but it's like those workers were just expected to die in that place, both at work and at home. There was no help for them, no one to tell them what their rights were.

The unions tried to help, but they weren't much good. They just took money from the workers and didn't do nothin'. The workers were so mistreated, they were like slaves. They were trapped in that place, with no way out.

Y'all know how some writers try to make ya feel a certain way about stuff? Well, this fella F. Scott Fitzgerald, he's a real pro at that. Sometimes he'll pair words together that just don't seem to fit, kinda like putting ketchup on your steak! But it works, ya know? He does this whole thing with colors too, like gold, green, white and gray, and red and pink. He builds up a meaning for these colors, like giving 'em a secret code, and then he uses 'em to make ya feel a certain way about somethin' important.  

He uses white and gray a lot, and they kinda mean the same thing but different. White's more fancy, like somethin' high class, while gray is old and faded, you know? He starts showin' ya this right from the beginning. Daisy and Jordan, they're always wearin' white. Everyone's wearin' white! Nick's got his white flannels, Tom's got his white shirt, and Catherine, she's lookin' like a ghost with all that white powder. It's like everyone's tryin' to be the same.

Then there's the gray stuff. Names at Gatsby's party, they're just gray on Nick's list. And the places, they're gray too. Cars, land, even a little kid, they're all gray. Like nothin' really stands out, ya know? It's all just kinda blendin' together.

Then Fitzgerald starts usin' these colors to make ya feel somethin' about certain people. Like Daisy, she's always in white. It's like she's not really a person, just somethin' Gatsby wants. Kinda like a trophy, ya know?

Howdy folks! Let me tell ya 'bout this real nice piece of land out in San Diego County. It's got perfect weather for growin' all sorts of good stuff - tomatoes, citrus, greens, squash, you name it! They even got a real hankerin' for organic food outta there, so much so folks are waitin' in line to get their hands on it. Eggs, milk, the whole shebang, all grown the natural way. 

And here's the kicker, this land ain't just good for growin' food, it's good for the critters too! You got your birds, your butterflies, all sorts of wildlife makin' themselves at home. Now, I know what you're thinkin', organic farming ain't always easy. Takes more elbow grease, that's for sure. But the reward is worth it, not just for the land, but for the folks who eat it too. 

This here land, it's right next to this big ol' forest, and it's got a history too, been farmed and used for years. But now, it's got a chance to be somethin' special, a place where folks can grow good food and good times.  I found a fella out there doin' just that, growin' organic, makin' a livin', and doin' right by the land. 

Now, if I were a farmer on this land, I'd be lookin' for a way to make it work, makin' money and keepin' it green. Might even get some help from the government to make it happen. And wouldn't that be somethin'?

Okay, so listen up, cause this is important stuff. See, when you're talkin' business, especially with folks from a different kinda place, you gotta understand their culture.  It ain't all sunshine and rainbows, and it ain't just one big ol' thing.  You can't just go around sayin' all Italians are loud or all Germans are strict. That's just plain dumb.

It's more like, you gotta figure out what makes them tick, y'know? What's important to them, what they believe in. That'll tell you how they're gonna play the game.  You might even see things through your own lens, but try to step back and see it from their side. 

Think of it like this:  if you're goin' to a potluck, you don't wanna bring the same dish everybody else is makin'. You gotta bring somethin' unique, somethin' that shows you understand what they like.  

And don't forget about the company you're dealin' with.  Even if they're from the same country, they might have their own ways of doin' things.  Some companies are all about workin' hard and long hours, others are more laid back.  You gotta figure out where they stand.

The bottom line is, you gotta respect people's culture, even if it's different from yours.  If you do that, you'll be a lot more successful in negotiatin' anything.

So, these guys, Anselm and Aquinas, they both think God exists, see?  They like to argue about it, though.  Anselm, he's all about faith, says you gotta look inside yourself to know God's there. Like, you think about God, and you just KNOW, right?  Doesn't matter if you can prove it or not, it's in your heart. Kinda like knowing your momma loves ya, even if she gets on your nerves sometimes.  

Aquinas, though, he's a bit more like, "Show me the proof, son!" He uses logic and stuff, like, look at the world, it's complicated, things happen for a reason, there's gotta be a big boss man behind it all. Kinda like figuring out a puzzle, you know? You got all these pieces, gotta be one missing, and you just KNOW what it looks like.

Both got good points, but neither of 'em really knocks it outta the park for me.

Listen up, folks! A long time ago, way back in like the 500s BC, there was this prince, see? He grew up, got tired of all the fancy stuff, and decided to find some real peace. He figured out some things about life, called himself Buddha, and started teachin' folks.  Those teachings, they became Buddhism, and the oldest kinda Buddhism, they call it Theravada.

Now, Buddhism's been around for a good 2,500 years, and it ain't exactly the same as when Buddha was kickin' around.  Take Sri Lanka, for example. They got this big water-cutting ceremony every year, lots of monks and regular folks doin' it. Buddha never said nothin' about that, but still, it's a big deal. See, Buddhism's changed over time, from the little stuff like ceremonies to the big ideas, the real heart of it all.  

Why did it change? Well, there's a bunch of reasons, some good, some bad.  Some stuff came from inside Buddhism, from the monks and the regular folks who follow it.  Other stuff came from outside, from folks who don't follow Buddhism at all. Some of that outside stuff was bad, tryin' to mess things up.  Other times, it was just neutral, didn't mean to help or hurt.

So, what's this Buddhism all about?  Well, Buddhists believe in the "Triple Gem": Buddha himself, his teachings (called the Dhamma), and the community of Buddhists (the Sangha). The Dhamma is like a big book called the Tripitaka, with three parts. One part has Buddha's words, another has rules for monks, and the last one talks about the deep, kinda mind-bendin' stuff about life.  Buddhists believe that life is full of suffering (that's called Dukkha), and that wantin' stuff causes that suffering (that's called attachment). But they also believe that we can get rid of suffering, if we understand these things and figure out how to let go. 

There are also rules for how to live, like don't kill, don't lie, don't steal, don't cheat, and don't get high.  Monks have even more rules to follow.

The most important thing in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths.  First, life is full of suffering.  Second, we make ourselves suffer by wantin' things. Third, we can stop sufferin'. Fourth, there's a path to stop sufferin', and that path is the Eightfold Path, which teaches us how to live a good life.

Well, lemme tell ya, the US and Mexico, they used to be at each other's throats somethin' fierce. I'm talkin' 57 years straight, from 1836 to 1893.  Like, they just couldn't stand each other!  The worst of it was that big ol' fight back in 1846, the Mexican-American War. The US jumped on Mexico and took Texas and the Southwest, all for themselves.  And it weren't just that one fight, they were always buttin' heads, right up until World War I.

See, they had all sorts of disagreements, like religion, culture, you name it. And money, always money.  Kinda like when your neighbor wants your lawnmower and you ain't lettin' him borrow it. You get me? It's like that with countries, too.  Especially when they live right next door, they're always lookin' at each other funny.

One fella, David M. Pletcher, he said back in '77 that the US had more problems with Mexico and Cuba than any other country.  And he's right, they're right there, practically in our backyard!  All the other Latin American countries, they get along fine with us, but not Mexico and Cuba.

Now, religion was a big one between the US and Mexico.  Just like folks fought over communism and fascism later on, back then it was all about Catholicism and kings and queens.  It was like a big ol' family feud, passed down from England and Spain, you know?  They just couldn't seem to trust each other.

Diehl and Goerts, they wrote a book about it, and they say there were 17 fights between the two countries in those 57 years. Most of it was about land, who owned what, and folks crossin' the border and causin' trouble.  Bandits and outlaws, they were a real pain in the neck back then.

But eventually, Mexico got hooked on the US, needed 'em for stuff, and America's focus shifted from takin' land to makin' money in Mexico.  And that's how it cooled down.

Fifteen years ago, bam! I got hit with this sickness outta nowhere. I'd been a nurse, figured it was a safe bet, ya know? Everyone said "You'll always have a job, folks get sick all the time." So, even though I always dreamed of being a scientist or a journalist, maybe both, I ended up a nurse.  Well, here I am, 46, single, not a dime to my name, and can't work. Still can't. Fifteen years on disability, and I got nothin' left. I make it by, but every day's a struggle, makes ya feel less safe, less secure, less like yourself. Nothing's certain anymore, except for one thing: I wouldn't be here without my family and a few good friends.  'Cause trust me, when life throws a curveball, you don't feel so tough.

Look, life throws ya curveballs, big and small, you know? No matter how prepared you are, sometimes life's just too big to handle alone.

I agree we gotta stop putting all our faith in the government.  It's about as reliable as a screen door on a submarine. But rather than everyone running around building their own bunkers, maybe we should learn to trust each other again, help each other out, ask for help when we need it.

These conservatives always yammer about "rugged individualism" building this country.  But what really got our forefathers through tough times?  It wasn't being tough, it was caring about each other, respecting each other, sharing what we had. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in those wagons? They didn't make it alone, they helped each other out.

So yeah, be prepared. I am. I got my emergency kit, first aid stuff, water purifiers, plastic sheeting for the windows if something nasty blows in. Flashlights, batteries, candles, matches, canned goods - the whole nine yards.  If you got the land and the know-how, grow your own food, can it, preserve it. Good idea. And a wood stove if you live in a place where you can have one.

But here's the thing: get to know your neighbors.

Alright, folks, lemme tell ya somethin' about these fancy science folks and their shells. They're tryin' to figure out how these critters, like snails and clams, build their shells, ya know, like how they grow and change 'em over time.  It's a real head-scratcher, 'cause these scientists say it's like tryin' to explain a fish swimmin' with math.

Now, they got these fancy programs, like CerioShell, that they use to make pictures of what these shells could look like. They take pictures of the shells, measure 'em up, and then throw 'em into this computer thing.  Then, they can fiddle with the numbers and see how the shell changes. Kinda like playin' with a toy, but with math!

They're talkin' about all these parts of the shell, like the whorls, the suture, the aperture, and the columella.  It's enough to make your head spin!  But basically, they're tryin' to figure out how these shells grow and change, like how fast the whorls get bigger and how the whole thing fits together. They want to know if there are rules, like a blueprint, that tells the shell how to grow.

So, they're lookin' at these shells like they're little time capsules, seein' how they change over time. They're usin' math and computers to try and crack the code of how these critters build their homes.  It's a mighty big puzzle, but maybe these scientists will figure it out someday.

Well, lemme tell ya, Indonesia ain't doin' too hot when it comes to baby health. 

For the last ten years, they ain't seen much change in how many babies die before they're a year old.  Now, they're doin' alright on some stuff, like makin' sure folks have clean water and toilets, but when it comes to makin' sure mama and baby are healthy, they're fallin' behind.  They gotta do better if they wanna reach their goals by 2015.

So what's the problem? Well, even though more folks are havin' their babies with a doctor or somethin', a lot of 'em are usin' midwives who ain't got the know-how to deal with complications.  That's why a lot of moms die from bleedin' after childbirth.  

And get this, fewer kids are seein' a doctor when they get sick with diarrhea.  We ain't got enough info on how well they're doin' after the baby's born, but it ain't lookin' good.

Now, they ain't doin' enough C-sections.  That's a problem in itself.  It's like a town-and-country thing – more C-sections in the city, nothin' in the sticks.  And the rich folks get better care than the poor folks.  You gotta wonder if it's 'cause they can't afford it.

So what do they do?  Should they just focus on fixin' one problem at a time, or should they just make the whole healthcare system better?  It's a tough one.

Fixin' one problem seems easier, but it can mess up other things.  They might pour all their money into one thing and forget about the rest.  And then you got a bunch of different programs, all doin' the same thing, but not talkin' to each other.  That's just a recipe for chaos.

Now, listen here, folks. Most of those fancy Victorian books are all about rich folks and their problems, right?  But there are a couple that are different, kinda like the redneck in a suit.  Take "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights" – they got a bit of mystery and strange stuff going on, which makes 'em stand out.  It's like they're saying, "Hey, even the fancy folks got secrets and crazy stuff happening in their lives!"

See, these books use mystery like a good ol' shotgun – it blasts open these characters and shows us what makes 'em tick.  

Take this quote from "Oliver Twist":

 *“And now, hosts of bewildering and confusing ideas came crowding on his mind. He seemed to be still walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said, sounded in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, … he found that he was talking to them…. Suddenly he started back at the report of fire arms; and there rose into the air loud cries and shouts; lights gleamed before his eyes, and all was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand bore him hurriedly away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which weared and tormented him incessantly.” 
(Dickens, 220)*

This poor Oliver fella, he's got all these crazy thoughts and visions swirling around him.  It's like he's caught in a nightmare, and he can't wake up.  He's hurtin' bad, and he's scared as all get out.  And the worst part is, he feels like he has no control over anything.

These books, they use dream-like stuff to show us what's going on inside these characters.  It's like they're letting us peek behind the curtain and see their true selves.

In "Oliver Twist", Oliver has these dreams, or maybe they're just flashbacks, where he relives the time he got shot.  It's like he's trapped in that moment of pain and fear again.



In "Wuthering Heights," they do something similar with "night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours."  

In both books, this mystery and confusion about what's real and what's not, it really helps us understand the characters better. It's like they're saying, "Life is messy and confusing, and even the folks who seem to have it all together are struggling inside."

A couple years back, I was workin' at this after-school program, helpin' out these little tykes with their schoolwork. I was pretty good at English and readin', so that's what I mostly helped 'em with.  One little fella, Adrian, probably in third or fourth grade, was givin' me a real run for my money. He was speakin' perfect English, but readin'? It was like he was speakin' a different language! Some letters he'd nail, others, not even close. It was just plain weird. You see, this kid was Latino,  and I figured maybe he was just learnin' to read in Spanish first.

Anyway, we were strugglin' somethin' fierce, until one day Adrian's mama showed up. Now, she didn't speak a lick of English, only Spanish. I was just learnin' a few words myself, but somehow we managed to get by. And then it hit me like a ton of bricks: Adrian wasn't readin' English 'cause he didn't know the alphabet real good!  We figured out he was just missin' some of those letters.  I don't know if that helped him much in the long run, but I sure hope he's doin' better now.

I tell this story 'cause it shows how we gotta take a closer look at the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. It ain't always as simple as it seems. Even a kid who speaks English like a champ can still struggle with readin'.  We all know this problem exists, so what do we do about it?  Well, for Adrian, it was pretty easy: some extra help with English readin' and learnin' the alphabet.  But for kids who barely speak English, it's a whole different ball game.

There ain't one magic solution. We gotta try a whole bunch of things, like dual language programs, lettin' kids learn in their own language while pickin' up English,  or havin' extra help from tutors who speak both languages.  We gotta combine all these things to make a real difference.

Dual language programs are a good idea, not just for kids speakin' Spanish, but for everyone. It helps 'em learn better, and it makes 'em more open to other cultures. Some folks worry it'll waste resources, but that ain't true. If we made these programs the norm, everyone would benefit.

Now, we ain't gonna ask every teacher to be bilingual, that's just crazy talk.  But we could easily have some extra help, some bilingual tutors or aides, to help those kids out.

We all get told somethin' 'bout somethin' bigger than us, somethin' we can't even wrap our heads around. Some folks go to church, some go to temple, some just sit and think about it. A lot of us just take what our folks told us, but some of us say "nope, not buyin' it!"  They say there ain't nothin' but what's right here, right now. We might believe one thing for a while, then change our minds and believe somethin' else. Doesn't matter what you believe, we all gotta figure out who we are, what we stand for. We're all lookin' for somethin' to light the way, somethin' to get us outta the darkness and into the sunshine.

My daddy, he loved cardinals.  We were sittin' on the porch, rain beatin' on the roof like a drum, smokin' a cigarette. The rain was comin' down in sheets, washin' over the plants by the porch. He looked out at the rain, like he was lookin' back in time, or maybe just lookin' for somethin' he'd lost. He'd gotten thinner, his clothes hangin' off him like a ghost.  His hair was thinner too, like the winter had taken a bite out of it.  He didn't look at me, just kept starin' out at the rain. I felt all alone, scared, like I couldn't talk to him 'bout missin' him 'cause talkin' 'bout it would make it real, for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair closer, and just looked out at the rain with him.

Daddy passed away that December, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation didn't take his pain away, just kept him around a few months longer than the doctors thought. I couldn't figure out why that was a good thing.  What kinda God would do that? I didn't say no prayers that night. If God was out there, he'd stopped listenin' to me a long time ago.

I didn't wanna see him die, so I didn't.  Couldn't watch the man who made me slip away. I wanted to remember him the way he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew him better than anyone else, better than his family even. I knew he wouldn't want me there watchin' him go. I just curled up in bed for three days and waited for the news.

Nobody even called.

So, these "Gothic Novels", they're kinda like a joke, right?  Like, they call themselves "Gothic" but they're really about somethin' new and shiny.  This guy, Ian Watt, he says it best, calls 'em "Old-New" oxymorons.  People have been talkin' smack about 'em, sayin' they ain't got no depth, but then they turn around and praise 'em for bein' all spooky and dramatic.  

 This first one, "The Castle of Otranto" by Horace Walpole, it's like the grandpappy of all Gothic Novels.  Walpole, he took all the old, fancy, theatrical stuff and mixed it with this newfangled way of writin' novels, where you get right inside the characters' heads.  He's talkin' 'bout  "old" stuff like medieval castles and whatnot, but he's doin' it in a brand new way.

 Back in Walpole's day, "Gothic" wasn't exactly a good word.  It meant somethin' old-fashioned and kinda dumb compared to all the fancy new stuff everyone was talkin' about.  But by mixin' that "Gothic" stuff with this new novel format, Walpole kinda made it work.  It's like, the Gothic stuff is all out there, but it's filtered through this modern lens, so it feels both old and new at the same time.

One of the big ideas in these Gothic Novels is this thing called "Chivalry".  They're all about knights and fancy knights-in-shining-armor stuff, you know?  Walpole, he was seein' all this mess in the world, all this political trouble, and he probably thought that maybe the knights of old were a lot better than the folks messin' things up now.   He's tryin' to show us this ideal of a knight, brave and honorable, and he's kinda makin' fun of the folks who ain't livin' up to it.  

Take this character, Frederic, for example.  He's a prince, he's suffered, he's been through a lot.  He's supposed to be this perfect knight, but Walpole's playin' around with that idea, makin' it a bit over-the-top.  It's like he's sayin', "Yeah, this is what a knight is supposed to be, but maybe it ain't so easy to be that perfect."

Well, lemme tell ya somethin' 'bout this here supply chain thing. It's like a river, see, startin' with the customer order and flowin' all the way down to the raw materials, makin' the product, and gettin' it to the customer's doorstep. This fella, Keith Oliver, he came up with the name back in '82. He said it's all about plannin', doin', and keepin' tabs on everything in that river to make sure the customer gets what they want, quick and efficient like.

Now, there's six main parts to this supply chain river, like six rocks holdin' it all together: makin' stuff, gettin' the stuff, keepin' track of the stuff, where it's at, how it moves, and the info flowin' around.  Managers gotta use these six parts to give the best service to their customers.

First up, you gotta make the stuff, see? That's the foundation, the bedrock of the whole thing. Figurin' out when, where, and how to make it all, that's what production's all about. Ya gotta know what the customer wants, what they're hankerin' for. Look at the market, that's your best bet. It'll tell ya what folks are buyin', what they need. Once ya know what folks want, you gotta decide what to make and how much. Then ya gotta figure out where to make it, which plant's got the best folks and the right equipment to make it good and keep 'em happy.

After that, it's all about plannin' the work, makin' sure the machines are runnin' smooth, and keepin' it all on track. Production's a big deal, every little bit counts. Mess up a step, and you could be losin' time and money down the road. I worked at Wal-Mart and Target, and lemme tell ya, they got a plan for everything, from how the uniforms look to how they unload trucks.  That's how they keep things runnin' smooth and efficient.

Next up, you gotta get the stuff. That's all about makin' smart choices about who's makin' what and where. Sometimes a company might have different parts makin' the same thing, each with their own equipment and workers. The manager has to figure out which part's best for each step.  Sometimes it makes sense to hand off some work to other companies, like outsource it. That's all about gettin' things done faster, cheaper, and better.

Well, lemme tell ya somethin'. This here Ellen Page, she's got herself a sign, see? Says Hitler's livin' it up in Burma.  Now, Burma, that's a place where them fellas in charge, they're real tough guys, kinda like those rednecks who think shootin' first and askin' questions later is the way to go.  

See, Burma's been ruled by these hard-as-nails generals ever since '62.  Back in '07, folks got fed up and started marchin' in the streets, like a bunch of righteous protesters.  They called it the Saffron Revolution 'cause them monks, they wear these bright yellow robes, see?  

At first, the government let 'em have their little parade, but then things got outta hand.  Them soldiers, they got all riled up and started tearin' up monasteries and arrestin' folks, even foreign fellas tryin' to take pictures. One of them guys, Kenji, got himself killed just for bein' there.

Now, this ain't nothin' new, folks.  Governments tryin' to keep folks in line, well, that's as old as dirt.  Remember back in Rome? Them emperors, they thought they were gods, runnin' everything.  And don't even get me started on those Japanese emperors, they think they're gods too! Even our own president, Bush, he's buddies with some preacher fella, Ted Haggard, who's head honcho of a group called Stupid People Worldwide.  Don't ask me how that works, it's a government thing.

There was this big ruckus in China back in '89, Tiananmen Square, where a whole bunch of folks were marchin' for freedom.  They say the government went a little overboard, killed a bunch of folks. Nobody knows exactly how many, 'cause them government fellas ain't very good at tellin' the truth.  And then there was that mess in Rwanda, where they went and killed all them Tutsis.  And let's not forget about Hitler, that fella who thought he was somethin' special and decided to wipe out all the Jews. 

The point is, folks, some folks just can't stand to see others livin' their lives, doin' their thing.  They gotta be in charge, gotta control everything.  It's a shame, really.

Now listen up, this Duke Ellington fella, he was a real whiz when it came to makin' music. He played piano, sure, but he was more of a big picture kinda guy. See, he knew how to make his band sing! He'd write these songs, real complex and groovy, that let each musician shine.  He'd give 'em a little wiggle room to freestyle, but he'd also lay down these tight, catchy parts that made each player sound like a million bucks. He knew how to make his whole band sound like one big, beautiful instrument. That's why he made some of the coolest jazz you ever heard!

This one fella, he wrote a book about Duke, said he used his singers like instruments, not just talkin' words. Like in this song "Creole Love Call", the singer's voice is like another instrument, addin' this kinda soulful texture without all the talkin'. And Duke knew how to make his singers fit right in with the band, too. 

This song, "Creole Love Call", it's like a slow, bluesy dance.  It's got these little sections, each one different, but they all fit together like puzzle pieces.  First, the singer and the woodwind players go back and forth, real smooth. Then, a trumpet player comes in, playin' low and mournful. Next, a clarinet player takes over, high and fancy. Then the whole band jumps in, makin' a big, bustling sound. Finally, the singer gets all raspy and growly, like he's singin' with his whole heart.

Duke was a genius, see? He knew how to make every part of his music come alive. He used singers, instruments, silence, everything to make his music sing!

And he kept doin' this, makin' more and more amazing music. In another song, "Hot and Bothered", he had a trumpet player and a singer trade licks, playin' off each other like they were one person. And in "It Don't Mean A Thing", he used a trombone player to start the song, makin' a sound so rich and full, ya just had to move.

She'd always felt like somethin' was missin'. Like there was a hole in her life that nothin' could fill. It started when she was about fourteen, just gettin' into the whole teenage thing. And three years later, at seventeen, it was still there. She figured out she wanted someone, not just stuff. But no boys ever really grabbed her attention. Some tried to chase after her, makin' all those clumsy moves to win over a girl who wasn't interested. Nobody really hooked her.

She'd often wonder about this weird thing, tryin' to figure out why she felt this way. She'd come up with theories over the years, but nothin' ever stuck. So she just kept livin' her life, always wonderin' about what she wanted.

Usually, days at home were pretty chill. Her folks were good, calm people. They never fought and, oddly enough, they hardly ever argued with her. The only time they butted heads was when she tried to be more independent and do her own thing. She was the daughter of a real easygoing couple, but she brought a whole lot of energy and fun to the mix. She was a real sweetheart, so naturally, folks liked her.

But today wasn't a calm day. She was wanderin' around the house, tryin' to find some inspiration for her own life, when she heard a little scream from the kitchen. It was her mom's voice, and it sounded scared. She ran into the room, panickin', "Mom! Mom, what's wrong?!"

Her mom was on the floor, holdin' her side and sayin', "Ow" in short gasps. Her daughter rushed to her side, "Mom, what happened? Where does it hurt?" Her mom pushed her hand away gently and said, "Sweetheart, I... need you to take me to the hospital." Her words were rushed and pained. "Okay, Mom, just tell me where to take you." Her mom pointed her hand towards the front door. The daughter was thankful she'd taken those self-defense classes. She lifted her mom gently, put her in the car, and drove like a bat outta hell.

At the hospital, she was surrounded by the smell of disinfectant and sickness, but she didn't even notice. All she could think about was her mom. She rushed her inside and started yellin' for a doctor. A few worried faces gathered around, and someone quickly brought in a gurney. They took her mom away for treatment, leavin' her daughter to sit and worry.

Turns out, her mom had fallen off a step stool while reachin' for a vase on the top shelf.

Alright, so listen up, folks! This study's about this fancy diet called the "Mediterranean Diet," but they call it "aMed" for short.  It's all about eatin' good stuff like fruits, veggies, nuts, and fish, and cuttin' back on the red meat and fatty stuff. Kinda like what your momma always told ya, right?

Well, this study wanted to see if eatin' this way could keep your heart healthy and stop you from havin' a stroke. And guess what? Turns out, it does!  They followed a bunch of nurses for 20 years, and the ones who ate like they were on vacation in Greece had less heart problems and strokes.  They even figured out that the more they ate like that, the better off they were.

Now, they asked these nurses about what they ate all the time, like a million times!  And they checked their medical records to make sure they weren't pullin' their leg.  They even took into account all the other stuff that could mess with the results, like smokin' and weight.

So, the bottom line is, eat like you're on a Mediterranean cruise and your heart will thank ya!

Well, back in '07, the whole country went belly up. Jobs disappeared faster than a politician's promise, houses were worth less than a pack of gum, and even the big, fancy companies were goin' broke. This mess still hangs over us like a bad hangover, so we gotta figure out what went wrong and how to fix it.

See, it all started with some folks in fancy suits makin' decisions that were about as smart as a fish wearin' a hat. They pushed banks and businesses to give out loans to folks who couldn't afford 'em - like givin' a kid a credit card and sayin', "Go wild!"

These fancy mortgage things, they got packaged up and sold all over the place. When folks started missin' payments, the whole system crashed harder than a drunk at a rodeo. 

It all started back in the Clinton days, when the prez was lookin' to stay in power. He wanted folks to think he was the best thing since sliced bread, so he loosened up the rules on loans. That was like lettin' all the air out of a tire - it looked good for a while, but it was just waitin' to explode.

Back then, folks were talkin' about how Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were gettin' pressured to give out more and more loans. People saw the writing on the wall, sayin' this was gonna end bad, just like when the savings and loan crisis happened.

You see, mortgages got all complicated. There were these adjustable-rate things, and these mortgage-backed securities, and these CDOs that sounded like somethin' outta Star Wars. Everyone got caught up in the housing boom, borrowin' more than they could handle. It was like a giant, wobbly tower of cards, just waitin' for the wind to blow.

And blow it did! The housing bubble burst, and all those fancy banks that bought up all those mortgages went belly up faster than a greased pig. The big five banks had trillions of dollars worth of mortgage debt - that's a lot of money! Some companies went bankrupt, others had to sell out cheap, and even the government had to step in and rescue a couple.

Listen up, folks! You know the drill, "Show, don't tell," right? But even a whiz at words like me sometimes gets caught up in the weeds.  Exposition, that's what it's called -  the part where you gotta lay down all the backstory, like a giant info dump.  It's like watching paint dry, or maybe worse, like someone trying to tell you every single thing about their cat's life.  Boring!

Exposition is when you just flat out tell the reader what happened, no fancy stuff. It's like one character in a movie just spouting off a whole history lesson.  Not cool. 

Think about it like this: You're reading a story, and bam, you're told the heroine met her man at the grocery store, they got hitched in a big ol' fancy wedding, and then, poof! Her hubby gets snuffed right in front of her.  You wouldn't want that whole thing taking up a couple pages, would ya?  You want to see their love, feel it, not just hear about it.

You gotta show us the husband's love for his wife, how he made her life better.  You gotta show us how she changed after meeting him.  That's what makes it real, makes you care.  Then, when he's gone, you'll be heartbroken right along with her.

So, as a writer, don't just hand us the bare bones of the story.  Give us the juicy details, the stuff that makes it come alive!

Well, I watched some news from Columbus, Ohio, you know, just keeping up with what's goin' on.  First up was NBC 4 this mornin' (August 13, 2011). They had this story about a fella in Ashley, Ohio, stabbed his wife somethin' awful.  Didn't say her name, but the creep's name was Shad Hostettler.  They showed his mug shot, and let me tell ya, the guy looked like pure evil. They only talked about it for a couple minutes 'cause it was still cookin'.  All they said was he stabbed her a bunch of times and got hauled off to jail. Seemed about right to me.

Then they had this story about a young fella, Travis Buyers, 18 years old, got shot up in Sharon Woods.  Critical condition, they said, and no one knew who did it.  SWAT was on the case.  This story felt kinda short, and you know what, I think it might be 'cause the fella was black.  Seems like the media only really cares when it's a white kid or adult gettin' messed with.  A black person gets hurt?  Lucky if they mention it at all.  

Next up, some knucklehead shot a hole in a Med-Flight helicopter.  .22 caliber, they figured, from a rifle.  Crime-Stoppers were offerin' five grand for any tips leadin' to the shooter.  

Then they talked about the rain comin' Saturday.  Said it'd be in the eighties all weekend.  Short story, I guess they wanted ya to stay tuned for more.

They had another one about a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road.  Said it was a black guy, dark-skinned they kept sayin', wearin' a hoodie.  Six foot tall, about 150 pounds.  Now, why they keep harp'n on the black part, I don't get.  

Finally, they had this fella, Rene Rodriguez, some big-shot drug dealer from Texas.  Convicted of sendin' pot all over Ohio. They said he got 300 months, which is 25 years, but why say it like that?  Just seems kinda fancy, don't it?  Oh, and they said he was Hispanic, but that didn't really have nothin' to do with the story.

Brothers, man, they got this crazy bond, you know? Like, it's unbreakable, like a chain forged in fire. It's got all these feelings in it, good and bad: love, pride, jealousy, even meanness sometimes. You can't explain it, but brothers get each other, see right through each other. It's like lookin' in a mirror, except the mirror's a little messed up, ya know? When things get tough, that bond really shows its true colors, for better or worse.  

Sometimes, that bond can be a heavy thing, cost ya somethin' precious. See, when you look your brother right in the eye, you see yourself, not how folks see you, but the real you, the good and the bad. It's in what you do and the stuff that comes after it that shows what you're really made of.

This story, "The Scarlet Ibis," it's all about that brotherly bond, the messy feelings that come with it. It's got these two brothers, settin' out on a crazy trip through a beautiful place, but it ain't all sunshine and roses. There's bitterness, there's pride, and in the end, only one brother walks away. 

The story's told from the older brother's point of view, and you can see all his tangled feelings pourin' out. He's got this pride, this need to be the best, and his little brother, Doodle, he just ain't cut out for that. Doodle's weak, can't keep up, and the older brother, well, he's got dreams of teachin' him everything, showin' him off as his own little sidekick. But Doodle ain't like that, and the older brother, he's gotta deal with that. 

He gets mad, even thinks about doin' somethin' terrible to Doodle. But then Doodle smiles, and the older brother, he sees somethin' in that smile, somethin' that melts his anger. There's love there too, but it's a complicated love. The story's all about how those feelings, those brotherly feelings, they can be a real mess, but they're a part of who you are.

Y'all ever think about how dang complicated our brains are? Back in the day, folks thought it was like a wax tablet, then a scroll, then a book. Now? They say it's like a computer. But listen up, those are just fancy ways to try and explain somethin' real complicated.

See, our brains, they take in all kinds of stuff from the world around us - touchin', seein', hearin', feelin' the heat. It's like a whole mess of signals, y'know? And our brains, they're like these whiz-bang machines, constantly workin' on makin' sense of it all. They take those signals, break 'em down, put 'em back together, like a puzzle. 

Sometimes they start from scratch, buildin' somethin' up slow, like when you see a box. At other times, they use what they already know to figure things out faster. Like, if you see a black box, they might already know it's a box 'cause you've seen 'em before.

But hold on, our brains ain't just processin' everything all the time. They got this filter, like a bouncer at a club, decidin' what's important and what ain't. It's why you can focus on your name in a crowded room but not on every blade of grass under your feet.

Now, to keep all this information around, our brains gotta store it. Think of it like a big ol' filing cabinet. There's different kinds of files, like ones for what you just saw, ones for what you're thinkin' about right now, and ones for memories you've had for years. 

And how do they organize all that stuff? Well, there's lots of theories about that. Some say it's like a big web, where ideas are connected to each other. Kinda like how you might link a picture of a chair to a picture of a table because they're both furniture.

So, yeah, our brains are pretty darn complicated. But ain't it somethin'?

Alright, so this Huxley fella, he’s talkin' 'bout how tech and money, they're gonna mess us all up real bad. He writes this story, "Brave New World," where folks are all about being happy all the time and lookin' out for themselves. They don't care much for thinkin' for themselves or bein' individuals, ya know?  

This World Controller guy, he’s like the big boss, tellin' everyone what to think and do.  It's kinda like how some folks think money talks, and if you ain't got it, you ain't got nothin' to say.  Huxley, he's worried 'bout that, see?

He uses this fancy talk, like "homogeny" and "reification," which means everyone's the same and stuff ain't what it really seems.  He's sayin' this whole system, with all the shops and stuff sellin' stuff, it's makin' folks dumb and happy, but not really happy, ya know?  

Huxley's talkin' 'bout how the rich folks, they got all the power and the poor folks, they just keep buyin' stuff they don't need. It's like they're blind to how it really works.  They're so busy thinkin' 'bout the next shiny thing, they don't see the big picture.

And the people in this story, they never really connect with each other. They're all just kinda floatin' around, doin' what they're told. Huxley might be sayin' that all this technology and money is turnin' us into robots, not really human beings anymore.

Alright, lemme tell ya 'bout this college campus here. Been here two and a half years, that's four and a half semesters, y'know? Getting around this place, it's a real pain, ain't it? My freshman year, they stuck me in East Halls, way out on the edge, further than the stadium and that big basketball place.  Walking to classes over by Willard, near the middle of campus, took me forever, like 25 minutes, especially when the weather was bad, which it always seems to be here in State College. I talked to one of these old grads, not much older than me, and he said back in the day, East Halls was way out there, surrounded by nothin' but empty land. Now they've gotta build all these sports fields, new buildings, even a new Creamery and health center, and apartments, all packed in tight. The more they build, the harder it is to get around. What's a fella to do?

Well, bikes, that's the answer, right? Except, you gotta have people ridin' 'em, and the place gotta be set up for bikes. I was talkin' to a buddy of mine, he'd been off bikes for a while, came back to it recently. He was sayin' he couldn't believe how good it was, how it was the only way to get around. Bikes are good for ya, they're quick, you can go a long way on a little bit of pedalin' and a bowl of oatmeal.  I live off campus now, just as far from the center as some dorms, and the smartest thing I did was buy a bike.

I got classes in Thomas building, a good 25-minute walk from my place. On my bike, it's like 5 minutes if I'm pedalin' hard. Problem is, Pollock Road's the quickest way there, and it ain't always easy ridin' on that road. Walkin' ain't bad, but I'm too busy for that. Without my bike, I'd be walkin' all the time, which is a whole bunch of extra time. Walking to Thomas every day is another 30-40 minutes, that's over two and a half hours a week, and that's just one class! Plus, I'd have to walk everywhere else too, appointments, other classes, you name it. No way I got time for that.

Culture plays a significant role in any negotiation. Culture can be defined as much by what it is not as what it actually is and what it signifies. Culture is not homogenous, nor is it a specific thing. It is also not singular or uniform. Statements such as “all Russians are stubborn” or “all Japanese are accommodating,” are inherently broad and overly simplistic. While the understanding of a culture’s generalizations are appropriate, it is much more productive to a negotiator to understand the significance of a culture to the matter at hand, and how that culture’s attitude can and will affect the table talks. When one approaches a foreign culture, one experiences it in a way that is relatable to his own culture, and comparisons necessarily arise. 

Attempting to understand a foreign culture or mindset can involve anything from studying its history to realizing its prejudices. Rather than judging or attempting to change a culture, one must simply accept it for what it is, and work within its boundaries, especially within the scope of negotiation, and most especially if one comes to the table with a weaker bargaining position. Likewise, if a negotiator finds himself on “away” territory, a respect for traditions and beliefs can only help in getting over any cultural barriers and move the negotiation forward.

It is important to note that culture does not necessarily limit itself to a national/international dichotomy. Most companies within a given nation establish their own corporate culture. For instance, a corporate culture might emphasize long hours in the office or a more relaxed schedule. Evidence of a corporate culture can be seen in employee dress codes, in communication style (direct v. indirect communication, delegation of duties), and hiring practices. Some companies encourage philanthropy at any level from employees, others restrict it to “company approved” charities or fundraisers. One need only look at the differences in American corporate culture from company to company (and indeed, intra-company diversity exists even from region to region, urban to suburban environments included) to appreciate the diversity of thought that can reside within a particular societal culture. Certain cultures are not nearly as stratified as American culture, and may appear more uniform to an outsider, but a similar exterior is simply a sign to dig deeper. 

Values are even more important to understand, because they provide the why of a culture. If saving face or communal harmony are valued within a culture, it is certain that a negotiator will not publicly shame his company or his superior in order to succeed at the negotiation table. Likewise, a negotiator from a culture which gives greater weight to a hard-driven bargain will not necessarily be driven to settle at the earliest opportunity. Taking these generalities into consideration is important before one gets to the negotiating table. However, a negotiator is well-served to learn something about his opponent on a personal level in order to make the negotiation effective.

“The fool hath said in his heart, ‘There is no God.’” The preceding quotation is seen first in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible, and is found at the beginning of St. Anselm’s argument regarding the existence of God. This belief seems to also be held by the other author whom we will be discussing, Thomas Aquinas.
